{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17478757","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17478757"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:15:49+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:15:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18808"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18808","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18808"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.16,0.65,0.02,0.06,0.12]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11541"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79404"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11541","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11541"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18808"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64726"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"985"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1177"},{"type":"tags","id":"1643"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"2756"},{"type":"tags","id":"4051"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"27163"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79404","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/79404"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA three-year-old boy presents to the Emergency Department with a two-day history of fever, lethargy, and widespread bruising. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. His immunisations are up to date. His parent reports he has had several episodes of epistaxis today.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 150/min, blood pressure 85/45 mmHg, respiratory rate 35/min, SpO2 94% on room air, and temperature 39.2\u00b0C. He has multiple petechiae and ecchymoses over his trunk and limbs. There is oozing from venepuncture sites.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHaemoglobin 95 g/L (105-140)\u003Cbr /\u003EPlatelet count 45 \u00d7 10\u2079/L (150-400)\u003Cbr /\u003EWhite cell count 25 \u00d7 10\u2079/L (4-11)\u003Cbr /\u003EInternational Normalised Ratio 2.5 (0.9-1.1)\u003Cbr /\u003EActivated Partial Thromboplastin Time 55 seconds (25-35)\u003Cbr /\u003EFibrinogen 0.8 g/L (2.0-4.0)\u003Cbr /\u003ED-dimer 8.5 mg/L (\u0026lt;0.5)\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Immune thrombocytopenia","Disseminated intravascular coagulation","Vitamin K deficiency","Von Willebrand disease","Acute leukaemia"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis child presents with features highly suggestive of disseminated intravascular coagulation (DIC). The diagnosis of \u003Cstrong\u003Edisseminated intravascular coagulation\u003C/strong\u003E is supported by the combination of clinical bleeding, thrombocytopenia, prolonged coagulation times (both INR and APTT), low fibrinogen, and markedly elevated D-dimer. The presence of fever and elevated white cell count suggests underlying sepsis, a common trigger for DIC.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EImmune thrombocytopenia\u003C/strong\u003E (ITP) typically presents with isolated thrombocytopenia but normal coagulation parameters. The presence of prolonged INR, APTT, and low fibrinogen makes ITP unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVitamin K deficiency\u003C/strong\u003E would cause prolongation of the INR but not the APTT, and would not explain the thrombocytopenia or elevated D-dimer. It is also rare in a well-nourished child with no underlying liver disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVon Willebrand disease\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with mucocutaneous bleeding and prolonged APTT but would not cause the constellation of abnormalities seen here, particularly the elevated D-dimer and low fibrinogen.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute leukaemia\u003C/strong\u003E can present with bleeding and abnormal blood counts, but would not typically cause such marked coagulation abnormalities at presentation. While it remains in the differential diagnosis, the acute presentation with fever and multi-system involvement is more consistent with DIC.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe key to diagnosis is recognising the combination of consumption of coagulation factors (leading to prolonged clotting times and bleeding) along with excessive clotting (leading to elevated D-dimer and consumption of platelets and fibrinogen). Treatment should focus on both supportive care with blood products and identifying and treating the underlying cause.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Disseminated intravascular coagulation (DIC) in children requires prompt recognition and treatment of the underlying cause.","Laboratory findings in DIC include prolonged coagulation times, thrombocytopenia, elevated D-dimer, and low fibrinogen.","Fresh frozen plasma and platelet transfusion are indicated for active bleeding in DIC."],"references":["Rajagopal R, Thachil J, Monagle P. Disseminated intravascular coagulation in paediatrics. Arch Dis Child. 2017 Feb;102(2):187-193. doi: 10.1136/archdischild-2016-311053. Epub 2016 Aug 18. PMID: 27540263."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64726"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18808"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64726","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/a